D0WE1MX08WW-kXifDGifkA
TL;DR: Excellent food, good atmosphere, service good but could improve. We've been to Nosh twice now, so I feel confident that our first two experiences are representative of a typical experience.   For starters, I had the Watermelon Chile Gazpacho. It's an interesting twist on gazpacho; a refreshing lite appetizer. The flavors are subtle and nicely balanced. I would've preferred a bit more chile oil heat, but that's not a criticism of the dish; I just tend to prefer more heat in my dishes than most people.  I ordered a traditional gin martini. It was made with "The Botanist" gin and was insanely good: smooth gin with a subtle juniper flavor, exactly the right amount of vermouth, served ice cold with a single blue cheese olive. Elegant, tasty and very, very dangerous. I can't wait to have another one.  The Charcuterie & Cheese Board was a pleasant surprise. It consisted of three different cheeses, (a gouda and two semi-soft goat cheeses), three sausages, (sopressata, capecola and chorizo), plus Chef Stacy's homemade baguettes, almonds and dried fruit. This style of appetizer is becoming more popular around town, but I have seldom seen it done this well. All three cheeses were interesting and flavorful and paired very well with the sausages. I'm really not a fan of sopressata, and this one did nothing to change my mind, but Caroline really enjoyed it. (Like the chile oil in the gazpacho, this is not a criticism, just a matter of personal taste.) What amazed me about the dish was the size of the serving: it was plenty of food for two people and would've made a sufficient appetizer for three people. I didn't expect to enjoy this nearly as much as I did. Very good.  The Pork Chop Calvados may have been the best pork chop I've ever eaten. "Subtle" is the key word on this dish. It was ridiculously moist and juicy and full of rich pork chop flavor, but the quality of the pork and the subtle complex flavors of the apple brandy cream sauce elevated this dish into the upper echelons of Chandler-area food. I normally try to eat my way through an entire menu before repeating anything, but I enjoyed this dish so much I am tempted to repeat it on my next trip to Nosh. It was that good.  Caroline raved about the lobster roll. I'm not a lobster roll fan, but I did taste the lobster; it was sweet and tender as fresh lobster should be. (I am amazed that we can get seafood this fresh in Arizona.) Her comments were that the meat was tender, succulent, sweet, fresh and not overcooked. The roll was grilled, buttered and served warm and absolutely stuffed with cold lobster; "the way it should be", according to my Boston-born-and-bred partner. The proportions between bread and lobster were right, but she would have preferred a less doughy roll. Not a criticism of the quality of the roll, just a preference for a different style of roll. Furthermore, she raved about the price: $21. She just paid $18 in Boston for a genuine Fanueil Hall lobster roll which wasn't as big and didn't taste any fresher. She said it was just as good as a real east coast lobster roll. High praise indeed.  She also had the Crab Salad  and commented that it was well seasoned, tasted fresh,  and was refreshing and light.   I've observed such a dearth of interesting desserts at most restaurants I frequent in Chandler that it made me suspect desserts were going out of style. But not at Nosh. Oh no.  If you ever doubted the existence of God, the Chocolate Bourbon Pecan Pie should restore your faith. I fear if I fully express how deeply and passionately I loved this dessert you would think me slightly unhinged. Just trust me: if you order nothing else, go to Nosh for the Chocolate Bourbon Pecan Pie. If you don't like it, leave the rest for me. I will eat the leftovers, then lick the plate clean, then probably lick up whatever crumbs fell on the table and finally sniff whatever Pecan Pie aromas remain in the air until I am sated.  Yeah, it was pretty good.  Ginger Chili coffee: I've never seen anything like this on any menu anywhere. I'll try almost anything with chile in it, so I had to try this. It was fun, subtle, (there's that word again), interesting and - most surprising - refreshing.  Seriously, even though it was hot coffee, the ginger-chili combo my refreshed my palate and cleared my head like ice water on hot a day. It was amazing & unlike anything I've ever tried. Definitely worth a repeat.  Caroline had the Deconstructed Coffee. She enjoyed it. I was too busy orgasming over the pie and coffee to give it my full attention, but it looked really fun  The atmosphere is casual and intimate, the music not too loud. My only complaint is that our waiters during both visits were not as intimately acquainted with the details of the menu as I would have preferred. This is an area where Nosh can improve, but it's only a tiny complaint as otherwise the service was attentive without being intrusive.  Highly recommended.

